data.content:
**What happened:** C# 14 introduces new built-in span conversions. Your `array.Contains(num)` now resolves to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Span-based methods **cannot be represented in expression trees**, so it throws at runtime.

**Fix:** Force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid. The same issue affects `.Reverse()` on arrays ã use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` there too.
